<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="586a5beb90d9908dc5528f9d0e11817c" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A guide to companions<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.12)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15286'>David "Wyvern" Cauwenbergh</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15286&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> August 7, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Well, this should be the first in a series of articles discussing some of the main companions and their gear in the Lord of the Rings TCG.  Although these articles are intended for beginning players, I do hope more advanced players will also find a couple of useful things.<br />
<br />
I&#8217;m not really used to writing articles, especially not in English since it&#8217;s not my mother tongue, so reviews and criticism are more than appreciated. =)<br />
<br />
For this first article, let&#8217;s start with my favourite, Aragorn&#8230; and in my opinion, when used properly, one of the best supporting characters in the game. With six different versions of this character out there, Gorn can be used in quite a variety of ways. Let&#8217;s have a look. <br />
<br />
Aragorn, Ranger of the North:<br />
<br />
Advantages:<br />
The ability to make him Defender +1 (at the cost of an exertion, however) makes this guy an excellent protector against swarm decks. When armed properly, Aragorn might even be able to win a couple of skirmishes, since minions in swarm decks usually have low strength. <br />
Give him a sword, pump him up with Sword Arm of the White Tower and you&#8217;ve got a lean mean fighting machine. <br />
This Aragorn also has the Ranger keyword, which means you can play a variety of stealth cards on him &#8211; a Ranger&#8217;s versatility, Pursuit just behind and Gondor&#8217;s vengeance &#8211; just to name a few.<br />
<br />
Disadvantages:<br />
The Defender +1 ability comes at the cost of an exertion. <br />
Yep, he&#8217;s a rare, so he&#8217;s quite hard to get.  The good news: he&#8217;s included in the First Anthology Tengwar set.  That should make our lives a lot easier =)<br />
<br />
Verdict: 4 out of 5<br />
<br />
Aragorn, Heir of Elendil:<br />
<br />
Advantages:<br />
Well to be honest, I really like this one. Even though he&#8217;s not a Ranger, you don&#8217;t have to exert this guy to make him Defender +1 and he always gets a maximum strength boost from Sword Arm of the White Tower. The fact that he&#8217;s a common makes him &#8211;in my opinion &#8211; a nice addition to the deck of a beginning player. <br />
He may be a good choice in HiDaN decks but what I prefer is to use him in combination with Gandalf Greyhame. Put a copy or two in your deck, discard him and bring him back at site 9. Even though poor Gorn will probably get slaughtered, this little tactic might just be enough to save your Ring Bearer, and win you the game.<br />
<br />
Disadvantages:    <br />
Once again, he&#8217;s no Ranger, but then again, he does have his strengths. <br />
<br />
Verdict: 4,5 out of 5<br />
<br />
Aragorn, Defender of Free Peoples<br />
<br />
Since Michael &#8220;Valdaris&#8221; Merkly already dedicated an excellent article to this guy, I&#8217;m not going to go into detail (see Aragorn, the Defender of Middle Earth). As Valdaris said, this version works best with elf decks, the other 4 lines of game text being somewhat less useful. <br />
<br />
Verdict: 4 out of 5 (since the elf ability really rocks!)<br />
<br />
Aragorn, King in Exile:<br />
Now here&#8217;s my favourite support character. His ability to heal another companion with the Aragorn signet might come in very handy indeed, especially since he can use the ability on himself too. I found it works fine in combination with Gorn&#8217;s bow, exerting him to wound a minion and afterwards healing him to allow a couple more exertions. Legolas Greenleaf, Gandalf Mithrandir, Boromir Lord of Gondor and Arwen Daughter of Elrond (yes indeed, some of the best characters in the game) can all benefit from Aragorn&#8217;s healing skills. <br />
Did I mention he&#8217;s a Ranger too?<br />
Disadvantages: none that I can think of&#8230;<br />
<br />
Verdict: 5 out of  5 : Da King rulez<br />
<br />
Aragorn, Wingfoot:<br />
<br />
I found this Aragorn to be the least appealing.  You don&#8217;t see him often since his use is limited to decks that make use of unbound hobbits&#8230; where he makes life easier for your fellowship when you want to double-move.<br />
No further comments on this guy&#8230;<br />
<br />
Verdict: 3,5 out of 5 due to his limited use&#8230;    <br />
<br />
<br />
Aragorn, Heir to the White City:<br />
<br />
Advantages: <br />
Well, here&#8217;s a nice one for a choke deck&#8230;<br />
Each time the fellowship moves during the fellowship phase, you may remove two twilight.  Very handy indeed&#8230; play Legolas for free I&#8217;d say.<br />
This Aragorn works fine in combination with other choke cards&#8230; Here&#8217;s a couple examples:<br />
No Strangers to the Shadow is an excellent way to reduce the twilight your opponent can work with and an Able Guide further helps you reduce twilight if you decide to double-move.<br />
Throw in Bill the pony and your opponent gets even less twilight.<br />
Legolas, Dauntless Hunter is great for choke too, especially in the early game. While your opponent&#8217;s conditions and events will cost a little more, he&#8217;ll have to choose whether to play a condition or a minion&#8230;<br />
And yep, this guy&#8217;s a Ranger&#8230;    <br />
<br />
Disadvantage:<br />
Only one I can think of&#8230; this guy&#8217;s on the x-list, too bad you can&#8217;t play him in Standard&#8230; <br />
<br />
Verdict: in open: 5 out of 5<br />
The Ranger&#8217;s gear<br />
Well, let&#8217;s have a look at the stuff Gorn has at his disposal:<br />
<br />
Aragorn&#8217;s bow:<br />
This card is a must in just about every deck that includes Aragorn. Try to include two copies of this since an exertion for a point of targeted archery is very useful.  Moria orcs bothering you? Just shoot them&#8230; One of Saruman&#8217;s guys trying to exert to use his special ability, try to make sure he can&#8217;t&#8230;<br />
Aragorn Greenleaf, what more can I say?<br />
<br />
Aragorn&#8217;s sword:<br />
So here you have the choice between Ranger&#8217;s sword and Ranger&#8217;s sword, blade of Aragorn&#8230;<br />
My choice goes to the first one. Damage +1 helps you kill minions so they won&#8217;t come back, and not everyone plays Uruks&#8230;<br />
<br />
Athelas:<br />
Get rid of those nasty blade tips and black breaths&#8230; or heal a companion, simple as that.<br />
<br />
Flaming Brand:<br />
Strength +3 and damage +1 against Nazgûl? Devastating! Give Gorn his Blade or another flaming brand and he&#8217;ll be able to deal with most Nazgûl with ease!<br />
<br />
Ring of Barahir:<br />
Even though spotting a culture token and healing a companion of that culture might come in handy in decks where your companions are going to take a lot of exertions, you&#8217;ll have to make sure your Aragorn doesn&#8217;t become the target of that nasty Grima Wormtongue&#8230;<br />
<br />
<br />
Deck Focus: the HiDaN deck:<br />
<br />
Here&#8217;s a deck that uses Aragorn as one of the key characters.<br />
A HiDaN deck (Help in Doubt and Need) is based on two cultures, Gondor and Rohan that work marvellously well together. <br />
Your typical starting companions are Theoden, TMoR and Eowyn, LoR. Theoden will be your main fighter. Aragorn (typically Heir of Elendil) is there to support him and to get rid of a couple of minions too.  Aragorn&#8217;s bow and cards like defend it and hope and Ithilien trap are there to make sure your opponent&#8217;s minions take enough wounds for your Theoden to make short work of them.  Help in Doubt and Need makes sure your guys win their skirmishes at the cost of an exertion. <br />
<br />
Here&#8217;s my HiDaN deck just to show you an example&#8230; : The free peoples side has 42 cards in it, so it&#8217;s supposed to be used in combination with a Moria shadow to allow for easy card cycling&#8230;<br />
<br />
Frodo, Old Bilbo&#8217;s Heir<br />
The One Ring, IB<br />
<br />
Eomer, TMoR<br />
Eowyn, LoR<br />
Aragorn, HoE x3 <br />
Boromir, DoMT x3 <br />
Faramir, SoD x2 <br />
Aragorn&#8217;s Bow x2 <br />
Ranger&#8217;s sword x1 <br />
Sword of Gondor x2 <br />
Eomer&#8217;s Spear x1 <br />
Rider&#8217;s Spear x2 <br />
frying pan x1 <br />
Firefoot x2 <br />
Brego x1 <br />
Bounder x1 <br />
HiDaN x2 <br />
Defend it and Hope x3 <br />
Armor x1 (always comes in handy against those Uruks) <br />
Athelas x3 <br />
Fortress Never Fallen x2 <br />
Ithilien Trap x2 <br />
An honorable charge x2 <br />
Simbelmynë x1 <br />
Swordarm of the White Tower x2 <br />
Ring of Barahir x1  <br />
<br />
Strategy:<br />
<br />
Eomer and Aragorn will be your main fighters, just make sure they are fully equipped. Use Gorn and his bow and Defend it and Hope to get those wounds on your opponent&#8217;s minions, and then use a frenzied Eomer to finish them off (Firefoot is included twice in the deck, should your opponent discard him). Gorn always gets the +4 bonus from swordarm of the White Tower. That should at least allow you to win a couple of skirmishes and get those tokens for Ithilien Trap. <br />
<br />
Your guys will be taking a lot of exertions, so healing might be very helpful indeed. The Ring of Barahir might come in very handy, Athelas too, but watch out for Grima Wormtongue! <br />
<br />
Even though you can&#8217;t use HiDaN with Faramir, I decided to include him in the deck anyway. He can still be exerted for DiaH and his game text&#8217;s quite cool too =) <br />
<br />
I hope they&#8217;ll remove the old Sting from the x-list. I really like the card, but since it isn&#8217;t standard, I decided to add a frying pan instead &#8211; let&#8217;s wound some orc =).<br />
<br />
Fortress Never Fallen helps you get rid of those annoying Moria and Sauron conditions&#8230; and gives you some tokens for the Ring of Barahir. <br />
<br />
Try to keep Eomer alive! Even though he might be able to handle the Balrog when fully equipped, you just can&#8217;t afford losing him. If he&#8217;s about to take his final wound, don&#8217;t hesitate to use Eowyn&#8217;s special ability! Make sure to get rid of any blade tips or black breaths your opponent throws at him. Remove them ASAP with some Athelas. Same thing with Aragorn.<br />
<br />
<br />
Well guys, that&#8217;s about it for now.  Thanks for reading, hope you enjoyed it!<br />
<br />
Cheers from Belgium!<br />
<br />
Next week: part 2 -  //Brothers in arms // - with a focus on Boromir, Faramir and a Ringbound Ranger Deck!<br />
